No BS cleanser by @faebeautyofficial 

First off, so happy that fae started skincare, it’s our favourite inclusive brand. 

We both used this cleanser from the lab trial phase to the final product and we have jotted down our thoughts on the same ! 

🥒 this is a simple, no active based, no bs cleanser. 
🥒 it has a viscous consistency, that lathers adequately 
🥒 this one does not dry out the skin at all, and is a lil hydrating 
🥒 1-2 pumps are enough for one time use. 
🥒 cleanses the face well without giving the squeky clean stretchy feeling. 
🥒 it is a perfect AM cleanser for all skin types, however would not work as a standalone cleanser in the pm routine for people who wear makeup and reapply sunscreen religiously (would be the perfect second cleanse)

“Barrier Damage” if you are into over using chemical exfoliants like me, then you’re no new to this term. Every skin reacts differently when their barrier is compromised, for instance my skin becomes red,itchy, tiny bumps all over and inflamed. 

I have been trying a lot of combinations for barrier supporting routines, and this one works so WELL in calming my inflammation and getting back my skin to normal. 

My three step routine consists of : 
A gentle cleanser 
Niacinamide serum (preferably 5%) 
A thicc ceramide based moisturiser 

I have been testing out low strength Niacinamide serums since a while now, and my first had to be from @reequil - the pore refining serum (5% Niacinamide) and here’s my review 👇🏼

- this formula is super lightweight and veryy hydrating 
- I have been using this for a little more than two months now
- This serum is my go to whenever my skin isn’t feeling the best, and it works it’s magic in a couple of nights 🙌🏼 
- It has worked very well on my existing blemishes as well as worked well in controlling breakouts 
- It works very well in controlling my sebum production! As good as any 10% Niacinamide variants 
- I have noticed a slight difference in the appearance of pores aswell, though nothing  major
- This can be incorporated while using any of the other actives in your routine 
- Code LTSSI gets you 10% off on reequil website (linked in bio) 
- What are your go to products/ingredients when your skin is messed up? Let me know in the comments below 👇🏼 
.
.

Azeclair serum from @beminimalist__ 

- This serum consists of Azeclair 17%, Propolis 4% and Matmarine 3% as its key ingredients. 
- 17% of Azeclair delivers 5% PAD, which is one of the best ingredients to look for if you have an acne prone skin (check more about PAD in our reels section) 
- The Matmarine, according to the brand claims provides sebum regulating properties (which I noticed to an extent but not too much) 
- I love how the serum is super lightweight 
- It’s literally the best serum I have put on my skin 
- It’s a perfect amalgamation of soothing and treating ingredients 
- The propolis is a cherry on top in this formulatian - litterally has helped healing my skin SO GODDAMN MUCH 
- I did see a difference in my redness (like y’all know i am basically a living red potatoe)
- My skin felt calm after every application 
- I have used it upto 4 times a week since more than two months now 
- Worked so well in controlling my breakouts, even during exam season when I break out a lot due to stress 🤩
- The best part? It pairs well with almost all the ingredients! I loved using this with Vitamin C & Niacinamide the most. However I wouldn’t recommend using this with exfoliating acids 
- I would definitely let this serum, sink in 
- This has to be my most favourite serum from this brand. 
- It retails for ₹700 and would last you about two months with regular usage

“Sunscreen is toxic!”
Every few months, a viral video appears claiming your sunscreen is secretly harming you. 
Usually by someone who looks like they have a great degree and spreads FOMO.

But here’s what you need to know:

☀️ Sunscreens are one of the most researched skincare products in the world.
Their ingredients go through rigorous safety testing often more than the makeup or moisturizers you use daily.
So why the fear?
🔍 These myths often start with:
Misunderstood studies 
(done on mice or unrealistic doses)
Outdated research
Or pure fear-mongering for clicks and views
The truth?
No reputable health body including the FDA, EWG, or dermatology boards has ever banned sunscreens for being “toxic” PERIOD. 

⚠️ The real danger is NOT wearing sunscreen.
Unprotected UV exposure causes DNA damage, premature aging, and increases your risk of skin cancer.
.
.

Joining the bandwagon of propaganda i am not falling for as someone who loves skincare & selfcare 🫶🏼

1. Sulphates shouldn’t be in your haircare : NO, sulphates are one of the most researched and most effective cleansing agents to exist! Yeah they do also exist in your detergent and soaps, but the concentrations matter, sulphates in haircare are the best especially for someone who has oily scalp and hair. If you have very thin/brittle hair, then you can skip them. Otherwise i would always recommend SULPHATE shampoos to everyone for an effective scalp cleanse. Remember the cleaner the scalp the better the hair health. 

2. Anything that claims to get rid of your acne overnight : not falling for such marketing claims is the best thing you would do for yourself! Acne needs time to heal and no skincare ingredient/product can completely heal it overnight. You can count on me, i try skincare products for a living ;) 

3. Skincare still being perceived as female thing : dear men your skin isn’t made of steel, go wash your face, moisturise and protect it from the sun, or idc 😘

4. Korean Skin lightening treatments : any skin lightening treatment will not work, YOUR SKIN COLOR CANNOT BE CHANGED, unless you wanna bleach off the upper layers of your skin and end up damaging and burning your skin :) 

5. A 10 step routine : you don’t need 10 steps to have a gealthy skin, stick to basics, you will surely see results with consistency.
6. No, expensive doesn’t always mean better! Look for the efficacy of the ingredient of your active ingredient in regards to the skin concern you have & not the price label :) 
7. Making sunscreen re application your personality: as much as i love my sunscreen, i don’t always re apply it unless and until i am exposed to sunlight for prolonged duration or outdoors. 

These are my personal opinions and if you @ me comments are open 🤭
.
.
.
